04253nam a22005535i 9780520922204DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209222047 a10.1525/97805209222042doi  a(DE-B1597)649027  a(OCoLC)1419789028  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh1 aFowden, Elizabeth Key, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBarbarian Plain :bSaint Sergius between Rome and Iran /cElizabeth Key Fowden; ed. by Elizabeth Key Fowden. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (254 p.) :b17 figures, including b/w photographs and line illustrations, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransformation of the Classical Heritage00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTE ON TRANSLITERATION -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tMAPS -- tIntroduction -- tONE Portraits of a Martyr -- tTWO Martyr Cult on the Frontier The Case of Mayperqat -- tTHREE Rusafa -- tFOUR The Spread of the Sergius Cult in Syria and Mesopotamia -- tFIVE Frontier Shrine and Frontier Saint -- tSIX The Cult of S. Sergius after the Islamic Conquest -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the fifth and sixth centuries A.D. there arose on the Euphrates frontier, between the empires of Rome and Iran, a city girded with glittering gypsum walls. Within these walls stood a great church, a shrine for the relics of Saint Sergius, who was martyred there, at Rusafa, in the early fourth century. Around Rusafa stretched the "Barbarian Plain," inhabited by Rome's Arab allies, many of whom revered the saint. Elizabeth Key Fowden examines the rise of the cult of Sergius in late antiquity, drawing on literary accounts, inscriptions, archaeology, images, and the landscape itself to construct a many-faceted picture of the role of religion in this frontier society. Focusing on the socio-cultural as well as the political dimensions of the Sergius cult, her study sheds light on the lives of the ordinary faithful, as well as on religion's place in the strategic calculations of hostile empires.Beginning with a detailed analysis of the surviving accounts of the martyrdom of Sergius, Fowden provides a discussion of Syrian Rusafa-Sergiopolis, traces the spread of the Sergius cult in Syria and Mesopotamia, and provides a provocative interpretation of the relation between the saint's presence at Rusafa and his role in frontier defense. She also discusses Arab Christianity in the context of late Roman culture in the East, as well as the continuation of the Sergius tradition after the Muslim conquest, emphasizing the changes and continuities brought by the rise of Islam.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAncient. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aKey Fowden, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021685340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092220440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520922204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520922204/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles